<DT><A HREF = "SPP16.HTM#AS502157">Roback: </A><DD>Clinton Brooks and Ron Lee from National Security Agency and Ed Roback and Raymond Kammer from National Institute of Standards and Technology acted as agency liaisons for committee arranging briefings and providing other information 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP16.HTM#AS502247">Rotenberg: </A><DD>Marc Rotenberg from Electronic Privacy Information Center and John Gilmore from Cygnus Support provided continuing input on number of subjects 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP26.HTM#AS717110">Russell Sage College: </A><DD>Caracristi holds BA from Russell Sage College and graduate of Federal Executive Institute 
<P><A NAME = "AX733287"></A>&#160;<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP27.HTM#AS733287">SIGSOFT Software Engineering Notes: </A><DD>Editor of SIGSOFT Software Engineering Notes for Association for Computing Machinery and chairman of ACM Committee on Computers and Public Policy 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP27.HTM#AS733345">SRI Exceptional Performance Award: </A><DD>Neumann awarded ACM Outstanding Contribution Award in 1992 and first SRI Exceptional Performance Award for Leadership in Community Service in 1992 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP6.HTM#AS1845">Safety margins: </A><DD>Public-key protection of secret keys used by products covered by Recommendation 4.1 to be allowed at least as strong as cryptographic protection of message or file text provided by products with appropriate safety margins that protect against possible attacks on public-key algorithms 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP27.HTM#AS7374">Schmults: </A><DD>Edward Schmults being senior vice president for external relations and general counsel for GTE Corporation from 1984 to 1994 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP3.HTM#AS1153">Secrecy: </A><DD>Cryptography policy being issue in which segments of population being stakeholders and invocation of official government secrecy in area having led to public distrust and resistance 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP15.HTM#AS4622">Secrecy: </A><DD>Secrecy being two-edged sword for democratic nation on one hand 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP15.HTM#AS46233">Secrecy: </A><DD>Secrecy having legitimate basis in situations in which fundamental national interests at stake 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP15.HTM#AS46412">Secrecy: </A><DD>Secrecy used to stifle public debate and conceal poorly conceived and ill-informed national policies and mistrust being common among responsible critics of government policy 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP15.HTM#AS464202">Secrecy: </A><DD>Government hiding poorly conceived policies behind wall of secrecy being not likely to trust government 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP25.HTM#AS67053">Secretary of Defense: </A><DD>Secretary of Defense to request National Research Council of National Academy of Sciences to conduct comprehensive study of cryptographic technologies and national cryptography policy 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP25.HTM#AS68021">Secretary of Defense: </A><DD>Secretary of Defense to direct National Security Agency 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP26.HTM#AS711175">Secretary of state: </A><DD>Dam served as deputy secretary of state and provost of University of Chicago 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP27.HTM#AS74192">Secretary's Advisory Committee: </A><DD>First chairman of American Federation of Information Processing Societies and appointed chairman of Secretary's Advisory Committee on Automated Personal Data Systems of Department of Health, Education and Welfare 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP16.HTM#AS4784">Securing Information Society: </A><DD>Title of report being Cryptography's Role in Securing Information Society 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP4.HTM#AS14683">Security: </A><DD>Emergence of significant foreign competition for U. S. information technology industry having number of possible long-term negative effects on U. S. national and economic security 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP27.HTM#AS729103">Security: </A><DD>Hellman's specialties being information and communication theory, cryptography and data security and international security 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP6.HTM#AS188208">Security applications: </A><DD>Bottom line for committee being DES being good enough for information security applications and likely to be good enough for next decade 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP2.HTM#AS674">Security classification: </A><DD>Conduct of debate regarding national cryptography policy complicated because certain elements of debate removed from public view due to security classification 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP15.HTM#AS47253">Security clearances: </A><DD>Legislation called for study to be delivered within 2 years after full processing of necessary security clearances and study committee accelerated work schedule to deliver report in 18 months from first meeting 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP17.HTM#AS50433">Security clearances: </A><DD>Working with Special Security Office of Office of Naval Research, Kevin Hale and Kimberly Striker of NRC's National Security Office having complex task of facilitating prompt processing of security clearances necessary to complete study in timely manner and managing security clearances 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP17.HTM#AS50434">Security clearances: </A><DD>Working with Special Security Office of Office of Naval Research, Kevin Hale and Kimberly Striker of NRC's National Security Office having complex task of facilitating prompt processing of security clearances necessary to complete study in timely manner and managing security clearances 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP19.HTM#AS551165">Security hole: </A><DD>Maintaining system security being difficult enough without deliberate introduction of potential security hole and introduction of another route of attack on procedures complicates job of information defender 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP2.HTM#AS87101">Security interests: </A><DD>Capabilities being important in varying degrees to protecting information security interests of different private and public stakeholders including law enforcement and national security 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP4.HTM#AS12996">Security mechanisms: </A><DD>Information security mechanisms for use that depend on secret algorithm or secret implementation invite loss of public confidence 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP4.HTM#AS1254">Security needs: </A><DD>National cryptography policy aligned with market forces to emphasize freedom of domestic users to determine cryptographic functionality, protection and implementations according to security needs as see fit 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP10.HTM#AS32064">Security needs: </A><DD>Information security needs in private sector in information age to be larger 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP2.HTM#AS6127">Security needs of businesses: </A><DD>Escrowed encryption being controversial because promotion by U. S. government appears to important constituencies to assert primacy of information access needs of law enforcement and national security over information security needs of businesses and individuals 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP13.HTM#AS403131">Security of electronic records: </A><DD>Broadening use of computers and computer networks generalized demand for technologies to secure communications down to level of individual citizens and assure privacy and security of electronic records and transmissions 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP15.HTM#AS44858">Security of terminals: </A><DD>Cryptography being not useful unless part of secure system and responsible for security to be concerned about everything from trustworthiness of individuals writing computer programs to be used to physical security of terminals used to access system 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP14.HTM#AS434237">Security policy: </A><DD>3 A number of other examinations of cryptography or information security policy being important to committee's work 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP4.HTM#AS13881">Security products: </A><DD>Controls used to deny potential adversaries access to U. S. encryption technology to reveal important characteristics of U. S. information security products or used to thwart U. S. attempts at collecting signals intelligence information 1 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP5.HTM#AS15863">Security products: </A><DD>Relaxation to encourage use of cryptography by creating environment in which U. S and multinational firms and users being able to use same security products in United States and abroad help promote better information security for U. S. firms operating internationally 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP7.HTM#AS2104">Security products of highest strength: </A><DD>Firms on list of approved companies being likely to have needs for information security products of highest strength possible for environment 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP2.HTM#AS814">Security requirements of information society: </A><DD>Committee found that current national cryptography policy being not adequate to support information security requirements of information society 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP1.HTM#AS41103">Security safeguards: </A><DD>Defending assets against information warfare and crimes of theft, misappropriation and misuse conducted by hostile nations, terrorists, criminals and electronic vandals being matter of national security and require high levels of information protection and strong security safeguards 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP10.HTM#AS316293">Security standards: </A><DD>Business and individual stakeholders not to have adequate representation in development of information security standards and export regimes 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP10.HTM#AS324195">Security threat: </A><DD>Government to take and role in collecting and disseminating information to promote awareness of information security threat 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP12.HTM#AS3736">Signals analysis: </A><DD>4 FBI proposes that TSC to provide law enforcement with capabilities in signals analysis 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP16.HTM#AS502323">Smoot: </A><DD>Rebecca Gould from Business Software Alliance, Steve Walker from Trusted Information Systems and Ollie Smoot from Information Technology Industry Council kept committee informed from business perspective 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP3.HTM#AS11578">Social consensus: </A><DD>Broadly acceptable social consensus that satisfies interests of legitimate stakeholders to be found regarding nation's cryptographic future 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP27.HTM#AS735185">Software Arts: </A><DD>Software Arts, Mr. Ozzie managed group responsible for porting VisiCalc and another product 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP6.HTM#AS19656">Software products: </A><DD>Administration proposed to give liberal export consideration to software products with 64-bit encryption provided that products escrowed with qualified escrow agent 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP12.HTM#AS37166">Software products: </A><DD>Automatic qualification refers to same procedure under which software products using RC2 or RC4 algorithms for confidentiality with 40-bit key sizes qualify for CCL 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP4.HTM#AS138215">Software-based products: </A><DD>Software-based products with encryption capabilities and cryptographic algorithms present more difficult challenge 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP17.HTM#AS50437">Special Security Office of Office of Naval Research: </A><DD>Working with Special Security Office of Office of Naval Research, Kevin Hale and Kimberly Striker of NRC's National Security Office having complex task of facilitating prompt processing of security clearances necessary to complete study in timely manner and managing security clearances 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP27.HTM#AS723160">Stanford University: </A><DD>Fuller received BS from University of Michigan (1968) and MS (1969) and PhD (1972) in electrical engineering and computer science from Stanford University 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP27.HTM#AS7293">Stanford University: </A><DD>Martin Hellman being professor of electrical engineering at Stanford University since 1971 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP27.HTM#AS729147">Stanford University: </A><DD>New York University and MS and PhD in electrical engineering from Stanford University 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP4.HTM#AS13810">State Department: </A><DD>United States controlled export of cryptographic technologies, products and related technical information as munitions administered by State Department 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP7.HTM#AS214117">State Department: </A><DD>Presumptive decision for cryptography submitted to State Department for export licensing for approval rather than disapproval 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP7.HTM#AS214162">State Department's licensing process: </A><DD>Efforts undertaken in years to streamline State Department's licensing process for cryptography exports to continue and strengthened 
<P><DT><A HREF = "SPP16.HTM#AS502325">Steve Walker: </A><DD>Rebecca Gould from Business Software Alliance, Steve Walker from Trusted Information Systems and Ollie Smoot from Information Technology Industry Council kept committee informed from business perspective 
